What is a Set in Python?
ðŸ‘‰ A set is an unordered, mutable collection of unique elements in Python.

Unordered â†’ elements have no fixed position.

Mutable â†’ you can add/remove elements.

Unique â†’ no duplicates are allowed.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Creating a set
s1 = {1, 2, 3, 4}
print(s1)   # {1, 2, 3, 4}

# Using set() constructor
s2 = set([1, 2, 2, 3])
print(s2)   # {1, 2, 3}

# Empty set (IMPORTANT)
s3 = set()   # {} creates an empty dictionary, not a set
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ðŸ”¹ Key Characteristics

Stores unique elements (duplicates automatically removed).
Elements must be immutable (numbers, strings, tuples).
Unordered â†’ no indexing, no slicing.
Supports set operations (union, intersection, difference).
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ðŸ”¹ Common Set Methods
s = {1, 2, 3}

# Add elements
s.add(4)        # {1,2,3,4}
s.update([5,6]) # {1,2,3,4,5,6}
======================================
# Remove elements
s.remove(2)     # Removes 2 (error if not present)
s.discard(10)   # Removes 10 if exists, else no error
s.pop()         # Removes random element
s.clear()       # Removes all elements
======================================
# Mathematical operations
a = {1, 2, 3}
b = {3, 4, 5}
print(a | b)   # Union â†’ {1,2,3,4,5}
print(a & b)   # Intersection â†’ {3}
print(a - b)   # Difference â†’ {1,2}
print(a ^ b)   # Symmetric difference â†’ {1,2,4,5}

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
âœ… In short:
A Set in Python is a mutable, unordered collection of unique, hashable elements.